helptext.en:
Abundance value – Is there high specimen abundance or an unusual abundance or association of fossils compared to deposits of a similar age?

Age determination – Does the specimen(s) or site advance biostratigraphic knowledge – zonal index species, zonal assemblage, short-ranging species, new stratigraphic range, exceptional stratigraphic exposure, or absolute age date from associated material?

Diversity value – Does a fossil sample or site have an incredible diversity of organisms, or preserve a whole ecological community of organisms as a life assemblage?

Exceptional preservation – Is there something remarkable about the type or quality of preservation? Does the fossil preserve soft (non-mineralized) tissue of a vertebrate, invertebrate, or plant? Are there articulated or complete specimens or fossil remains in amber? Do specimens occur in place?

Education value – Is the site of interest for museum-quality specimens? Could the specimens or site be used as for teaching and public education? Does the site have potential as an interpretive site for cultural tourism, ecotourism, or as a recreation site for public use?  

Heritage value – Is the site within a park? Is the site considered important by the local community or Indigenous community? Does the site have historical interest related to fossil exploration? Is the site visited by recreational paleontologists, school groups or tourists? Does the site have related geological landmark significance (type section or geomorphological feature such as Hoodoos)?

Holotype – Is the specimen a holotype, the name-bearing representative of a new species?

Paleobiogeographic interpretation – Do the fossils give insight into geographic distribution of the biota?

Paleoclimate interpretation – Do the fossils provide information about past climate change?

Paleoecological interpretation – Do the fossils add scientific context about the biota, communities or ecosystems? Are trace fossils present that record activities?

Paleoenvironmental interpretation – Do the fossils help interpret past depositional conditions?

Paleogeographic interpretation – Do the fossils provide context for past conditions such as latitude or tectonic setting?

Rare – Is the fossil extraordinary due to its geographic or stratigraphic location (e.g., the first of its kind in B.C. or North America) or is it a rare discovery due to remarkable morphological or anatomical feature(s)?

Taxonomic Value – Is the taxon previously unknown or possibly a new taxon (family, genus, species)? Does it have morphological variation compared to known taxa? Is the taxon important to evolutionary relationships?

Vertebrate – Are the fossils rare vertebrate remains or traces including skull, bones, teeth, feathers, bone bed, skin impressions, burrows, tracks, coprolites, or gastroliths?

helptext.en:
Geological Group or Lithodemic/Lithotectonic Grouping – Select unit from which fossil was sampled:

  • Stratigraphic Group (or Supergroup) or
  • Lithodemic grouping such as a Complex or
  • Lithotectonic grouping such as an Assemblage

Geological Group Uncertain - Check the box if you are unsure of the Group or Grouping term.

Geological Formation – Select the stratigraphic Formation (or equivalent term) from which the fossil was sampled.

Geological Formation Uncertain – Check the box if you are unsure of the Formation.

Geological Member – Select the stratigraphic Member from which the fossil was sampled.

Geological Member Uncertain - Check the box if you are unsure of the Member.

Informal Map Unit or Name – If formal stratigraphic rank names (group, formation, member) do not apply to the rocks sampled, select an informal stratigraphic name or map unit name from which the fossil was sampled.

Other Informal/Other Unit Name – Enter the informal rock unit name or map unit name (or code) if the unit is not found within the existing picklists.

Sample left in situ – Check the box if the sample was left in the outcrop.

Repository or Institution Number – Enter an assigned repository or storage number for a fossil sample.

Repository Name – Choose the name of the museum or institution where the fossil sample is stored.

Repository Location Uncertain – Check the box if your are unsure of the storage location.

Field Number – Record a sample number assigned to a fossil sample in the field.

Storage Notes – Add other information related to storage of the fossil sample or details about sample left in situ.

Age undetermined – Check the box if the age of the fossil could not be determined.

Minimum time - Select the youngest age for the fossil.

Minimum time uncertain - Check the box if you are unsure of the age assignment.

Maximum time - Select the oldest age for the fossil.

Maximum time uncertain - Check the box if you are unsure of the age assignment.

Common Name Uncertain - Check the box if you are unsure of the common name.

Fossil Identification Uncertain - Check the box if you are unsure about either or both the Genus and/or species name.

Fossil Size Category - Choose if the specimen is a macrofossil or microfossil. If the sample contains both, indicate this in the Fossil Notes.

Additional Taxonomic Information - Note other taxonomic information such as:

  • Assign a formal higher taxonomic name if specimen is not identifiable to Genus and species (e.g., Actinopterygii) or
  • Assign informal taxonomic designation (e.g., chimaeroid) or
  • Note alternate scientific names (e.g., if taxon name changed over time such as Alnus crispoides = Alnus hollandiana).
  • Do not repeat common names here.

Other Fossil Part or Fossil Part Details - If the term you are looking for is not listed under Fossil Part, provide the fossil part name or list the specific type of body part (e.g., type of bone).

Other Trace Fossil or Trace Fossil Details - If the term you are looking for is not listed under Trace Fossil, list the specific type of trace fossil.

Fossil Condition – Select if specimen is complete or a fragment.

Fossil Preservation – Select type of preservation.

Fossil Notes – Enter relevant information to help classify the fossil.
